		<tr valign=top>
			<td class="BoardRowB" colspan=2 width="83%">
				This is one of the more whiny complaints I've seen. <br>  <br> First of all, I can pretty much identify what class many characters are on sight.  I look at their armor and weapons.  Of course, this isn't surefire, but a wood elf carrying a staff or a scimitar is most likely a Druid, for example.  High elves wearing metal armor and carrying swords are invariably paladins.  Someone with the sword/shield pet is an Enchanter, and someone with an Elemental is a Magician (duh).  Etc.  I've been wrong on occassion, but I'd say I'm right about 80% of the time. <br>  <br> Also, as the first responder said, /consider works on players as well as it does on monsters.  Since my first character was on Sullon Zek, /conning other players is almost habitual on my part. <br>  <br> And, god/dess forbid, you could actually talk to other players.  You know, socialize?  Roleplay? <br>  <br> Frankly, I'm not sure I believe that you've spoken to &quot;over 100 people about this&quot;, and even if you have, I suspect the real reasons people left FV is because a) there are lots of barriers set up to prevent twinking (and reading the EQ official message board about people who intend to twink their Vah Shir, clearly many people do this and many people can't stand the game without doing it--their loss, really) and b) the language barrier, even with the fix, makes certain kinds of grouping impractical, even if not barred by the (apparently bugged) alignment grouping rules. <br>  <br> Lots of the &quot;l33t d00d&quot; players think the only way to play is if the warrior is a troll, the wizard is a gnome or erudite, and the cleric is a high elf or dark elf.  In FV, such a group would experience something of a communications problem.  Races are gently nudged to group with members of their own race, which mitigates against certain kinds of power-gaming.  Frankly, it's more practical to have groups that competently share a language. <br>  <br> Lasgalen		

			</td>
		</tr>
