		<tr valign=top>
			<td class="BoardRowB" colspan=2 width="83%">
				Anon is practically necessary from a roleplaying standpoint. THINK for a moment. Now, Steve is a peerless rogue, the pilferer of all goods that aren't nailed down, and some goods that were nailed down poorly. Now, what good is it to Steve if EVERYONE knows he's the famous thief. Now, let's look at it this way- do -you- want that righteous paladin knowing exactly who, where, and how strong your necromancer is? Now, so what if /anon makes finding a group somehow harder...news flash, folks. Realistically speaking, I can't tell how good a kendoist without seeing his Men cut. Now, extremely skilled people might be able to tell the person's skill in the way that they move, but I can't spot it myself. So...lurk around near where you would hunt at your level..Roleplay, for chrissake, while you wait. Maybe you'll discover what people find fun in it, and realize how pathetic 'must be 35 levels over the poster' sounds. Now, for some descriptive writing, the RP and the Game aspect. <br>  <br> GAME- <br> Level 7 Cleric waiting for a group outside BB. Sees a Barbarian who proceeds to cast third circle spells, and is a yellow con. A Barby Shaman of level 9. /invites the barby, then helps him heal up. No speaking needed, no /whos. <br>  <br> RP- <br> You're sitting on BB, picking off the gnoll spawn, when the barby shows up. You can pinpoint his skill, as a fellow 'worshipping' caster, just by looking. You can piece together the exact level by watching what is cast. You offer, without exactly needing words, your aid, by casting buffs and heals and gesturing to the shaman that you wish to help.
						<p><span class="SignatureTitle">-----signature-----</span>
						<div class="SignatureText">
						Ahadiel, 7th Season Champion of Hibernia <br> Raguel, 6th Season Warden of Hibernia <br> Guinivere, you're the one, making gametime so much fun <br> &quot;Sleep well. Forever. Have a million sweet dreams&quot;- Mature <br> 
						</div>
							

